  "prompt": "Why all planets are circling the sun in the same direction?",
  "response": "The fact that all the planets in our solar system orbit the Sun in the same direction is primarily due to the way the solar system formed. About 4.6 billion years ago, the solar system formed from a giant rotating cloud of gas and dust known as the solar nebula. Under the force of gravity, this nebula collapsed and began to spin faster as it contracted, much like a figure skater pulling in their arms to spin faster. This conservation of angular momentum resulted in the formation of a flattened, rotating disk.\n\nThe Sun formed at the center of this disk, while the remaining material within the disk gradually coalesced to form the planets, moons, asteroids, and other bodies. Because all these bodies formed from the same rotating disk, they inherited its overall direction of rotation and orbital movement. As a result, they all orbit the Sun in the same direction, known as prograde motion, which is counterclockwise when viewed from above the Sun's north pole.\n\nAdditionally, most planets also rotate on their axes in the same direction as they orbit the Sun, though there are some exceptions, such as Venus and Uranus, which have unusual rotational characteristics likely due to collisions or other significant events in their past.",
